8) main.py RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
main.py is an entrypoint only.

main.py may:
- load config
- initialize services
- register providers
- loop through provider execution
- call sync orchestration
- report summary logging

main.py may NOT:
- contain full parsing implementations
- contain raw DB query blocks
- contain matching logic internals
- contain normalization logic internals
- contain provider-specific hacks
- grow into a god file

main.py should read like orchestration, not implementation.

Good:
- initialize sync_service
- build providers list
- execute provider.fetch_and_parse()
- sync normalized events
- log totals

Bad:
- 300+ lines of provider-specific branching
- inline HTML parsing in main.py
- raw Supabase code in main.py
- sync fallback logic hardcoded in main.py

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
9) FUNCTION AND METHOD DISCIPLINE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
All functions must be:
- short
- focused
- explicit
- readable
- named by intent

Rules:
- one function should do one thing
- prefer early returns
- avoid deep nesting
- avoid giant try/except around everything
- extract helpers when logic grows
- avoid vague names
- avoid giant parameter lists

Preferred names:
- fetch_raw_events
- fetch_event_details
- parse_event_card
- parse_occurrence
- normalize_title
- normalize_venue
- build_occurrence
- create_fingerprint
- find_existing_match
- sync_event
- deactivate_missing_events

Forbidden naming style:
- process
- handle_data
- do_sync
- run_all
- temp
- temp_fix
- fix2
- final_final
- new_code

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
10) DATA CONTRACT RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Raw external data is untrusted.
Normalized models are the internal contract.
Persistence payloads are explicit outputs.

Rules:
- do not pass loose dicts everywhere
- use explicit models for normalized data
- source name must be explicit
- external_id must be explicit when available
- source_url must be explicit when available
- datetime fields must be normalized consistently
- occurrences must be explicit objects when repeated date structure exists
- optional fields must remain intentional
- invalid fields must be sanitized before persistence

Do not confuse:
- raw payload
- normalized model
- persistence/update payload

These are different layers and should remain separated.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
11) SUPABASE / PERSISTENCE BOUNDARY RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Supabase access must be isolated.

Mandatory:
- all Supabase access goes through clients/ or repository-like boundary
- sync services orchestrate persistence but do not scatter raw SDK code everywhere
- provider code must not write directly to Supabase
- persistence methods must be explicit and traceable
- writes must be controlled and observable
- sync must be idempotent where possible

Forbidden:
- direct Supabase write from provider
- raw upsert logic duplicated in random places
- hidden schema assumptions in magic strings across many files
- uncontrolled mass update scripts without explicit intention
- silent partial failure on writes

Persistence code must respect:
- shared schema
- backend/flutter dependencies
- field consistency
- future maintainability

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
12) MATCHING / DEDUPLICATION RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Matching logic must be centralized.

Rules:
- matching heuristics belong in shared service layer
- fingerprint logic must be explicit
- text normalization used by matching must be reusable
- thresholds must not be hidden in unrelated files
- provider-specific hacks must not silently override global behavior
- duplicate prevention is mandatory when providers overlap
- false positives and false negatives must be inspectable during development

Do:
- centralize fingerprint creation
- centralize title/date/location comparison logic
- document why a match is accepted
- keep matching deterministic and testable

Do not:
- duplicate matching logic per provider without reason
- hide fuzzy logic in utils with no visibility
- blend parsing and matching into a single unreadable function

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
13) SCRAPING / FETCHING RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Use the lightest reliable approach.

Priority order:
1. public API / structured endpoint
2. RSS / JSON
3. static HTML requests + parsing
4. browser automation only if necessary

Mandatory:
- explicit timeouts
- explicit retry rules where justified
- explicit user-agent/session handling where needed
- parsers/selectors must be easy to update
- source-specific fetching stays source-specific
- abusive request patterns are forbidden

Forbidden:
- endless retry loops
- random sleeps everywhere
- scraping + DB write in same function
- browser automation by default
- hidden anti-bot tricks scattered across project
- large scraping scripts with mixed responsibilities

Provider fetch code should fail clearly enough to debug.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
14) CONFIGURATION RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
No hardcoded secrets. Ever.

Mandatory:
- API keys from environment
- Supabase URL from environment
- Supabase key from environment
- configurable sync mode
- centralized settings access
- clear failure when required config is missing

Current acceptable state:
- config.py is acceptable for now

Future growth rule:
- if config.py becomes crowded, split into:
  - config/__init__.py
  - config/settings.py

Rules:
- do not call os.getenv randomly in every file
- do not hardcode environment-sensitive URLs
- do not duplicate environment parsing across modules
- runtime modes must be explicit:
  - live
  - dry-run
  - debug
  - local/dev if needed

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
15) ERROR HANDLING AND LOGGING RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
No silent failures.
No swallowed exceptions.
No bare except without intention.

Logs must clearly show:
- which provider failed
- which stage failed
- which event or record failed
- whether failure is fetch / parse / normalize / match / sync / persistence
- whether retry is safe
- whether failure is partial or fatal

Rules:
- log for operational clarity, not noise
- actionable messages only
- provider failures should be distinguishable from system failures
- one failing provider must not automatically corrupt the whole pipeline
- use structured, readable logging wherever possible

Bad:
- “Something went wrong”
- silent pass
- giant catch-all exception with no context

Good:
- provider=mobilet stage=parse external_id=123 failed because missing detail url
- provider=kultur_istanbul stage=sync record_title=... failed due to Supabase timeout

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
16) TESTING RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
All important shared logic must be testable without running full live scraping.

Priority test areas:
- date parsing
- text normalization
- title normalization
- normalized model mapping
- provider parsing with fixtures
- fingerprint generation
- duplicate detection
- sync idempotency
- event active/inactive lifecycle behavior
- provider parser resilience

Mandatory:
- tests must be placed under tests/
- provider tests should use fixtures when possible
- tests should validate deterministic outcomes
- debug scripts are not a replacement for tests

Preferred organization:
- tests/utils/test_date_parser.py
- tests/utils/test_text_normalizer.py
- tests/providers/test_kultur.py
- tests/providers/test_mobilet.py
- tests/services/test_matching_service.py
- tests/services/test_sync_service.py
- tests/integration/test_provider_to_sync_flow.py

Rules:
- avoid root-level test clutter
- avoid tests that only print output without assertions
- parser experiments may exist temporarily, but stable verification must move into tests

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
17) DEBUG / PROBE / EXPERIMENT RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Debugging is allowed.
Chaos is not.

Debug/probe scripts are useful for:
- inspecting raw source responses
- validating selectors
- checking JSON payload shape
- reconciling DB state
- validating search/index behavior
- testing one provider in isolation

But:
- they must live under scripts/
- they must not become permanent root clutter
- they must not duplicate production logic unnecessarily
- they must not silently mutate production data unless explicitly designed for it
- output files must go to artifacts/, not root

Rules:
- read-only debug scripts should be clearly separated from mutating scripts
- probe scripts should have narrow goals
- once debug logic becomes reusable, move it into services/utils/tests
- long-lived debugging value should become real tooling or tests

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
18) CLEAN CODE ENFORCEMENT
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Mandatory:
- descriptive names
- small files
- small classes
- small functions
- intentional boundaries
- low side effects
- explicit data flow
- minimal duplication
- readable branching

Forbidden:
- giant utility modules
- commented-out dead code
- hidden magic constants everywhere
- duplicated parser code across providers
- debug leftovers inside production paths
- “just for now” architectural violations
- vague helper files with unrelated code
- output files committed randomly without purpose

Comment rule:
- comments explain WHY
- code explains WHAT
- do not use comments to justify bad structure

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
19) FILE SPLITTING RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Split by responsibility early.

If a file starts mixing:
- fetching
- parsing
- normalization
- matching
- persistence
- retries
- debug exports

then it must be split.

Healthy examples:
- one provider per source
- one sync service
- one matching service
- one Supabase client
- one date parser
- one text normalizer
- one normalized contract module

Rule:
If a provider file starts carrying too much detail parsing or subflows,
consider splitting internally by source concern.

Example:
- providers/mobilet.py
may later become
- providers/mobilet/fetcher.py
- providers/mobilet/parser.py
- providers/mobilet/mapper.py

Only split when complexity justifies it, but do not wait until chaos is severe.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
20) CHANGE MANAGEMENT RULES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Every change must define:
- what stays the same
- what changes
- why it changes
- why the new structure is cleaner

Rules:
- no refactor should secretly introduce behavior change
- no quick provider fix should break shared matching
- no schema-impacting change should be hidden inside unrelated cleanup
- behavior changes must be explicit
- architecture cleanup must not silently alter business outcomes

When changing a provider:
- preserve normalized contract
- preserve sync expectations unless intentionally updated
- verify matching still behaves correctly

When changing persistence:
- verify downstream compatibility
- verify idempotency assumptions
- verify null/optional field handling

